18 2021-03-13 fever At approximately 2 PM on Wednesday the 10th, I began to feel light headed, nauseous, and feverish. C... Read more
Close
At approximately 2 PM on Wednesday the 10th, I began to feel light headed, nauseous, and feverish. Color drained from my face and I also began to lose track of the conversation I was having. I couldn't keep up with the pace of the conversation and eventually realized I couldn't remember what we were talking about. Looking back on the event now, I could only remember what was happening for around. 2 minute span before I forgot it. After losing my ability to form new memories, I began to lose old ones. I would look through pictures and not recognize faces, listen to songs and not remember the artists, and lose entire gaps of my past. My parents described my memory loss as that of a concussion but, to be frank, I don't remember much of any of it. All of my past memories have returned, but I still have yet to regain my memory from 2 PM to 10 PM of that day.

18 2021-04-17 malaise, sweating, fatigue, fever History of Present Illness: Patient is a 18 y.o. male with no pertinent past medical history who pr... Read more
Close
History of Present Illness: Patient is a 18 y.o. male with no pertinent past medical history who presents to the ED with complaints of chest pain. The patient notes that he started noticing chest pain this AM after he woke up that is associated with nausea. The pain is described to be in the center of his chest and is persistent. EMS was called who administered 2 SL NTG and 1 dose of ASA 325 mg. He notes that he received his 2nd Moderna vaccine on Thursday April 15th. He is currently a senior in High school. He had no adverse reactions to his 1st dose of the Moderna vaccine but after the 2nd dose he notes that he was having fever, malaise, body aches, and decreased appetite. He also tells me that he has been so fatigued that he has not really gotten out of bed in the last 48 hours. In regards to his oral intake he had (1) 16.9 oz bottle of water yesterday and nothing else but did have a glass of orange juice and some cereal this morning. During my evaluation with the patient he notes that he is still having chest pain that he reports to be retrosternal any 5/10 in severity. He denies any radiation into the left arm or jaw. He feels the pain is worse with movement and better when he is resting. He has had associated nausea and shortness of breath. He has been having low-grade fevers at home but denies any coughing, abdominal pain, diarrhea, dysuria, burning or itching with urination, congestion, rhinorrhea. He denies any tobacco use, drug use, alcohol use. In the emergency department initial workup is notable for potassium 3.6, magnesium 1.7, phosphorus less than 1, troponin 7206 with repeat at 10,212. 19 2021-04-19 sweating Patient had parked in the COVID vaccine waiting area, and was observed to fall forward onto his stee... Read more
Close
Patient had parked in the COVID vaccine waiting area, and was observed to fall forward onto his steering wheel within a few minutes of parking by 2 other participants waiting in the car next to him. One of them immediately notified one of the parking lot volunteers who came and got me within 1 minute of this observation. 2 students and I came quickly to the open drivers side door and began talking to assess the situation. Mr. Bannister appeared pale, mildly diaphoretic (sweating) and slightly confused as to the passage of time, but was able to state and spell his name and talk coherently about his circumstances. He stated that he was not allergic to anything that he knew about, and that he had no prior history of similar reactions to vaccines or medicines although he had not taken any shots in several years. He noted that he had not eaten anything since breakfast (now mid-afternoon). He described himself as initially feeling weak, faint, and nauseated with his vaccinated arm feeling heavy and numb. He also reported that he had a sensation of blurriness before passing out, but denied any spinning sensation, visual loss or ringing in the ears. There were no obviously visible abrasions or bleeding on his face or forehead. The nursing students brought a chair, and we elevated his legs and gave him some water to drink during the time we were monitoring his vital signs. He refused a cupcake because of the nausea, but as time progressed he gained facial color and was more comfortable in conversing. His hands had equal muscle grip and strength, visible fingernail beds were pink and his capillary refill was less than 3 seconds. Towards the end of our monitoring, he did accept some nuts and M & Ms to eat. A University Safety Medical Report was completed by the appropriate safety personnel. He was fully AAO x 3 at the end of our monitoring, and stated that if he felt better he would drive to his apartment (less than 5 minutes away) but would wait for his girlfriend to get out of class if he did not feel fully capable of driving. We encouraged him to eat something light when he got home, to use cool water/warm water soaks at his shot site, exercise his arm, and to take an NSAID for pain relief the next day. We recommended that he eat something light before his second shot (which had already been scheduled), that he bring someone with him the next time, and as a precaution to wait 30 minutes following the second shot. He left at 3: 15 pm driving his car without any apparent difficulties. An online report was completed for the incident 04/20/2021.

On 10-Apr-2021, the patient experienced LOSS OF CONSCIOUSNESS (Short time "everything come black"/ short time "black down") (seriousness criterion medically significant), PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Sore arm), NIGHT SWEATS (Night time sweat), MUSCLE DISCOMFORT (Short time "lost control of muscle of neck"), DIZZINESS (Dizziness) and HEADACHE (Headache). On 11-Apr-2021, NIGHT SWEATS (Night time sweat), MUSCLE DISCOMFORT (Short time "lost control of muscle of neck"), DIZZINESS (Dizziness) and HEADACHE (Headache) had resolved. At the time of the report, PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Sore arm), HYPOSMIA (Partially lost smell) and DYSGEUSIA (Partially lost taste) outcome was unknown. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. Concomitant medications use was unknown. No treatment information was provided. 20 2021-04-16 fever My 20-year-old son received his first Moderna shot on March 16, 2021, at his college health clinic w... Read more
Close
My 20-year-old son received his first Moderna shot on March 16, 2021, at his college health clinic with no obvious side effects. He received the second Moderna shot at the same location on April 13, 2021. On the morning of April 14, 2021, he began running a high fever with repetitive vomiting and stomach cramping. He did not immediately seek medical attention because he had been told of side effects of the vaccine. When it was no longer tolerable, he reported to the local ER where it was later discovered he had a 4 mm kidney stone, which he passed two days later. We were told that the kidney stone would likely have begun forming about 31 days earlier, which would approximately coincide with his first COVID injection. There is no family history on either side of any kidney stones in the family. While my son's lifestyle may introduce some risk factors for kidney stones, I felt it was reasonable to report it as potentially relating to the vaccine.

After the 2nd dose, he noticed arm soreness at the injection site more quickly than before. 10-12 hours later, he noticed headache and subjective fever, which was relieved by Tylenol. On Wednesday he woke up with subjective fever and chills, and felt sternal chest pain during deep breathing and attempted cough, but did not notice any effect from positional changes. Other than attempting to cough to elicit pain, he did not experience any other symptoms such as runny nose, coughing, sneezing, congestion, shortness of breath, palpitations, abdominal pain, diarrhea, or dysuria. The following day, he noticed that the chest pain was more severe and persistent throughout the day. The pain location would vary from the sternal area to the left side of his chest. The intensity of pain would vary between a 2-3/10 to 7-8/10. When the pain peaked, it would be accompanied by feelings of fever, chills, and brief headache, and he felt that the pain would "spread" across his chest. The pain would persist for a variable amount of time but then eventually disappear before returning. The pain was not affected by deep breath, position, or analgesics (he took an ibuprofen at around 2 AM when he couldn't sleep). After he fell asleep he was not woken up by pain. On Friday, he pain continued to be intermittent, and peaked during a work meeting. At that point he told his boss and an MD co-worker, who recommended that he presented to the ED. The EKG that was obtained in triage showed sinus tachycardia widespread ST elevations, PR depressions, with reciprocal changes in aVR. At this time he was continuing to experience chest pain. After getting a room in the ED, he no longer felt pain. He received a 2nd EKG showing improvement in ST elevations in some, but no all leads. He received ibuprofen and he continued to feel no symptoms. He was found to have a troponin elevation of 8.84 that peaked to 11.2. Transthoracic echo showed no motional wall abnormalities, normal EF, no pericardial effusion. He was admitted to the CICU out of concern and workup for myopericarditis.

Bloody diarrhea; Ulcerative colitis; Dizziness; Feeling "very sick"; Fatigue; Fever; Chills; Headaches; Nausea; This spontaneous case was reported by a physician (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of DIARRHOEA HAEMORRHAGIC (Bloody diarrhea) and COLITIS ULCERATIVE (Ulcerative colitis) in a 22-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. The patient's past medical history included Asthma and Eczema. On 05-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 09-Apr-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 09-Apr-2021, the patient experienced DIARRHOEA HAEMORRHAGIC (Bloody diarrhea) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), COLITIS ULCERATIVE (Ulcerative colitis) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), DIZZINESS (Dizziness), MALAISE (Feeling "very sick"), FATIGUE (Fatigue), PYREXIA (Fever), CHILLS (Chills), HEADACHE (Headaches) and NAUSEA (Nausea). On 09-Apr-2021, DIZZINESS (Dizziness), MALAISE (Feeling "very sick"), FATIGUE (Fatigue), PYREXIA (Fever), CHILLS (Chills), HEADACHE (Headaches) and NAUSEA (Nausea) had resolved. At the time of the report, DIARRHOEA HAEMORRHAGIC (Bloody diarrhea) and COLITIS ULCERATIVE (Ulcerative colitis) outcome was unknown. DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS (normal ranges are provided in parenthesis if available): In April 2021, Colonoscopy: abnormal (abnormal) it appeared to be an "ulcerative colitis" on the entire colon. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. Concomitant medication mentioned topical cream NOS for eczema. Treatment information mentioned IV Methylprednisolone and Metamizole. The patient received both scheduled doses of mRNA-1273 prior to the events, therefore action taken with the drug in response to the events was not applicable. Company comments This case concerns a 22-year-old female hospitalized with serious unexpected events of diarrhea hemorrhagic and colitis ulcerative, nonserious unexpected dizziness, malaise, and expected pyrexia, chills, headache, fatigue, nausea. Event onset 24 hours after second dose mRNA-1273. Serious event outcomes unknown. Based on current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

* Tuesday, March 16th, I received my first Moderna shot. No immediate symptoms, felt fine. * Thursday, March 25th (9 days post-vaccination), I was sitting at my desk and experienced some kind of visual distortion (my computer monitor bounced up and down 4 times in quick succession, even though I was perfectly still). Got up from my desk and laid down, and it went away. * Tuesday, March 30th (two weeks post-vaccination), I started experiencing persistent dizziness/imbalance. It was manageable for the first couple of days, and I still went about my daily activities. * Thursday, April 1st, symptoms got noticeably worse. I had a really bad episode of vertigo/dizziness in the afternoon. This spell of bad symptoms lasted until Saturday evening/Sunday morning. I wasn?t falling down, but I would describe it as akin to being on a boat in rough seas or a plane flying through a storm. Pressure in head and ears was intense. I?ve had longstanding tinnitus, but pitch/volume definitely seemed to change somewhat. My neck was incredibly stiff, and my throat felt somewhat ?tight? (tonsils or lymph nodes in neck felt enlarged). Took ibuprofen and Benadryl on and off over next several days. * Tuesday, April 27th, symptoms are ongoing. Still having imbalance, dizziness, and non-spinning vertigo, though less severe than previously.

Pt felt nauseous, hot, started getting red, and sat down on floor about 5 minutes after receiving the vaccine. I was alerted and I helped him into the vaccination room to lay down on the floor with his feet propped up. His girlfriend was there to help calm him down. I offered to call 911, he refused. Patient is a 22 y.o. male with no previous cardiac history, no known cardiovascular risk factors, and no significant past medical history. 2 days ago he received his second dose of the Maderna Covid vaccine. Yesterday he reported flulike symptoms with fever to 102 degrees, generalized myalgias, and fatigue. He awoke at 2 AM this morning with sharp somewhat diffuse substernal pain unrelated to activity, inspiration, exertion, position, without radiation or associated symptoms. He took Tylenol which eventually caused the pain to decrease in intensity. He called his family, discussed it with his girlfriend, did some online research, and came to the ER for evaluation where his EKG demonstrated anterior T wave abnormalities and his high-sensitivity troponin came back elevated at 16,072. His pain is now fully resolved, he is being admitted to the hospitalist service, and cardiology consultation was requested. June 6, 2021

Early on in the day of 1/6/21, I felt very sluggish and spaced. My boss asked me early in the day if I was okay because she said that I seemed "out of it." It wasn't to the point that I was unable to work, but it was a noticeable difference from my typical state. At 11:31 AM, I texted my wife and said "I feel gross and weird today." When she asked me how so, I replied, "I just feel run down, my neck hurts, and I can't focus." My arm was more sore than it typically is from the flu shot, but it wasn't unbearable. As the day went on, I felt the cloudiness in my head start to dissipate a bit and I started to feel a little better. By dinnertime, I was feeling sick to my stomach and was not able to eat very much. I chose to head to bed around 9 because I was feeling pretty ill (my neck had really started feeling sore again and my stomach was very upset.) At 1:30 AM on 1/8/21, I woke up with a horrible headache. I get migraines from time to time, but this was unlike anything I had ever felt before. It felt like my head was in a vise and I was very close to asking my wife to take me to the ER. I never go to the doctor, but it legitimately scared me. My neck was extremely sore and my head hurt so bad that even laying it on a pillow hurt. I was extremely nauseous as well. I took a few extra strength Tylenol and laid my neck on a heating pad with an ice back on my forehead. The sound of our humidifier was too much for me, so I also out in earplugs. After an hour or so, I fell back asleep. When I woke up this morning, I still had a headache and I took an Excedrin. To this point, I have felt a little sick to my stomach, but the intense headache has been kept at bay. My neck is still sore but it is also somewhat better.

Starting about 10 hours after receiving the second Modern vaccination I experienced a minor headache and drowsiness, which continued until about 30 hours after the vaccination. These symptoms resolved without treatment. Around 20 hours after the vaccination an itchy rash developed on the lower lip, around the left eye, and in the genital area (including: penis, testicles, and upper inner thigh). Rash continued to get worse until about 4 days after the vaccination. At this point I sought treatment at a local urgent care. The urgent care personnel said they believed the rash symptoms were caused by the Modern COVID-19 vaccination, did not identify any other possible causes, and encouraged me to report it to the VAERS system. The treatment followed was topical 1% hydrocortisone cream applied to the affected areas, and 12.5 mg of diphenhydramine taken orally before bed. The rash symptoms improved with treatment but have not fully resolved at 5 days after the vaccination.

I did not feel anything shortly after the injection, but later in the evening, started to develop a normal post-vaccine soreness. I thought little of it and went to bed. I woke up just after 3am with chills, fever, and worsened arm pain, to the point that it restricted my arm's range of motion and speed of motion. Interestingly, the arm is not red or swollen, but is painful near the injection site, and the area around my clavicle on that side is somewhat swollen, but not red or painful (likely a lymph node). I was unable to get back to sleep due to these side effects (primarily chills and fever). After a few hours of trying to get back to sleep, I took some Tylenol and tried to eat breakfast. I was unable to keep much down, and had to arrange a day off of my internship, and was finally able to sleep on and off for the next few hours. The symptoms have somewhat lessened, but have not resolved, after about 22.5 hours post-injection. I fully expect this to resolve or mostly resolve by the 48 hour mark. I mostly found this unusual due to the severity of the reaction and after only the first dose, and wondered if my young age could have something to do with the clearly robust immune response so soon after inoculation.

Initially I had experienced the standard adverse effects of drowsiness, a little difficulty sleeping, minor chills. The next day following my Dose 1 of the Moderna Vaccine, I started noticed chest pains on both sides of the chest. It wasn't from breathing and not very consistent or something I could re-create on command. It seemed to happen every hour for a few seconds and was a sudden, sharp pain. That was a concern for me so I did some basic internet searches and found that Chest pains are a symptom of the vaccine. I didn't think too much of it after that but It was a concern I kept in my head. My timeline gets a little foggy here but either that same day or the following day, the chest pains were still happening and I wasn't feeling 100%. One evening I went to take a bath. As I was laying in the water, my heart rate felt off, almost as if it was skipping a beat or not in the right rhythm. I remember laying in the bathtub, trying to count my pulse or seeing if I could "catch" the incorrect beat. Rather than one normal heartbeat it felt like there was 2 beats very closely timed with each other. My heart rate felt faster than normal considering I was only laying down in water and didn't do any exercises the past few days. Unfortunately I never was able to find a good way to track the pulse and timing, but I was sure that something was wrong. I had difficulty sleeping that night because I kept feeling something wrong with my heart rhythm. I got worried that I would need to go to the emergency room, but I told myself to sleep it off and if the chest pains and awkward heart beat continues for 5 days, I would go see a doctor. As for an outcome, thankfully I stopped noticing it around day 4 and haven't had chest pains since. I am extremely worried as to how my body will react to Dose #2.

Patient is a 24 y.o. male with no significant past medical history who presented on 6/25/21 with intermittent headaches. Patient states he was in his normal state of health but after receiving the COVID-19 vaccination on May 1, he developed a headache shortly after and since then has been having worsening headaches with associated sinus congestion. CT head was done at that time which showed some sinusitis. His headache worsened since then prompting evaluation at an outlying facility. Further evaluation at that facility revealed venous sinus thrombosis on CT head and patient was subsequently started on full dose Lovenox and transferred to ED. MRI brain here also revealed thrombosis of dural venous sinuses. Patient was admitted to the ICU for close neurologic monitoring. He was evaluated by neurology. In the ICU patient remained medically stable. He was deemed stable for non-ICU level of care and transferred to the hospitalist to continue care. Heme-onc was consulted. Patient was evaluated by heme-onc and recommended transitioning to Eliquis and discontinue Lovenox to avoid the possibility of having a HIT type of reaction. Hypercoagulable work-up was initiated hematology recommended Eliquis for 3 months and to follow-up with a local hematologist for discharge follow-up. Patient was cleared for discharge from neurology and hematology standpoint. Patient symptom was controlled on tramadol and Zofran. It was felt patient received maximum benefit of hospitalization and deemed medically stable for discharge. Patient was seen contact his primary care physician who states he will enter the referral to hematologist. Return precautions was discussed with patient and his wife.

At approximately 12:45pm on 4/27/2021, patient received his first dose of Covid19 (Moderna) vaccine, given by Pharmacist on duty. During the 15 minute observation period following the vaccine, the patient's father asked the pharmacist to check his blood pressure. While the pharmacist was checking his blood pressure (approximately 2-3 minutes following the vaccination), she notices the patient was starting to look pale and shut and squint his eyes as if he was having trouble focusing his vision. The pharmacist questioned the patient to make sure he felt ok, and the patient said his vision was going black and he was getting dizzy and lightheaded. The pharmacist moved nearby objects out of the way to prepare to lay the patient on the ground. When returning to the patient, he was staring blankly, hunched over, unresponsive, no pulse felt on a 5 second check, and had rheum dripping from nose and eyes. At 12:50pm the pharmacist instructed technician to call 911. Patient was lowered to the floor in the supine position where he remained unresponsive and no pulse could be felt on a 10 second check, but chest rise could not be evaluated as patient started to have convulsions. Convulsions ceased after approximately 15 seconds and patient started groaning and moving his head and said he could hear but he couldn't open his eyes yet. Patient remained supine and the Pharmacist continued to carry on conversation with patient until EMS arrived at 12:57pm to evaluate patient. EMS attributed the instance to syncope related to the vaccine. The patient denied ambulatory care to the hospital for any further evaluation. Patient denied history of fainting expect for ?one unprovoked episode at his grandmother's house when he thinks his blood sugar got too low.?

24 hours after the second Moderna dose, I began to feel very weak with a strong headache and a low grade fever. By Thursday (48 hours after vaccination) the headache was very strong and by that night it was debilitating. The fever had increased as well to between 101-102 degrees. Thursday night Friday I treated symptoms with alternating doses of Ibuprofen and Acetaminophen, which succeeded in reducing the fever but did not rid of the headache. Saturday the debilitating headache persisted with extreme light sensitivity and nausea. The pain became so great Saturday night that my wife took me to the Emergency Room. There they performed a brain scan with an MRI that came back normal and treated the pain with Morphine. I was sent home around 8am Sunday morning with a prescription for Toradol. The pain did not decrease with the Toradol and by 6pm Sunday I was vomiting blood and the pain was excruciating. At the advice of my primary care doctor, I went back to the Emergency Room. In the Emergency department they performed a Lumbar Puncture and collected spinal fluid for testing, as well as blood for lab work. The pain was managed with Fentanyl. Late that evening the Hospital admitted me. I was given two more MRI's of the brain - one with contrast. I also underwent an upper scope of my esophagus, stomach, and upper colon which found 3 small ulcers likely due to the high volume of NSAID pain relievers taken over the previous days. The lumbar puncture revealed that my white blood cell count was 51 and they officially diagnosed aseptic meningitis.

Acute myocarditis; Substernal chest pain; Chill; fever; This literature-non-study case was reported in a literature article and describes the occurrence of MYOCARDITIS (Acute myocarditis), CHEST PAIN (Substernal chest pain), CHILLS (Chill) and PYREXIA (fever) in a 25-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. LITERATURE REFERENCE: Acute myocarditis after a second dose of the mRNA COVID-19 vaccine: a report of two cases. Clinical Imaging. 2021;78:247-49 No Medical History information was reported. On an unknown date, the patient received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient experienced MYOCARDITIS (Acute myocarditis) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant), CHEST PAIN (Substernal chest pain) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), CHILLS (Chill) (seriousness criterion hospitalization) and PYREXIA (fever) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). The patient was hospitalized from sometime in 2021 to sometime in 2021 due to MYOCARDITIS, then for 3 days due to CHEST PAIN, CHILLS and PYREXIA. At the time of the report, MYOCARDITIS (Acute myocarditis), CHEST PAIN (Substernal chest pain), CHILLS (Chill) and PYREXIA (fever) was resolving. DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS (normal ranges are provided in parenthesis if available): In 2021, Angiogram: normal (normal) normal coronary arteries. In 2021, Blood pressure measurement: borderline (Borderline) 129/75 mmHg. In 2021, Body temperature: high (High) 39.1 degree celcius. In 2021, C-reactive protein (0-0.5): high (High) 25 ng/ml. In 2021, Echocardiogram: normal (normal) normal function and no significant valvular disease; ejection fraction was 55%. In 2021, Electrocardiogram: abnormal (abnormal) mild conclave ST elevation with no reciprocal changes. In 2021, Heart rate: normal (normal) 76 bpm. In 2021, Magnetic resonance imaging: abnormal (abnormal) normal left ventricular function, , subepicardial late gadolinium enhancement in the anterolateral wall of the mid and apical left ventricle, increased T1 (1450-1550 ms), T2 significant intensity (54-60 ms). In 2021, Oxygen saturation: normal (normal) 98%. In 2021, Red blood cell sedimentation rate (0-15): high (High) 25 mm/h. In 2021, Respiratory rate: normal (normal) 20. In 2021, Respiratory viral panel: negative (Negative) negative. In 2021, SARS-CoV-2 test: negative (Negative) negative (1 of 1) and negative (Negative) negative (2 of 2). In 2021, Troponin I (0-0.032): elevated (High) 14 ng/ml, elevated (High) 20.4 ng/ml on hospital day 2 and elevated (High) declined to 9.5 ng/ml on the morning of hospital day 3. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown), the reporter considered MYOCARDITIS (Acute myocarditis) to be possibly related. No further causality assessments were provided for CHEST PAIN (Substernal chest pain), CHILLS (Chill) and PYREXIA (fever). Concomitant product use was not provided. Treatment information was not provided. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product, and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
